## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker` Component

---

## The Two Major Issues

### Issue 1 — Missing Dependency Array (Runaway Effect Execution)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
}); // ← No dependency array!
```

Without a dependency array, `useEffect` runs after **every single render** — not just on mount. The scroll handler calls `setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, and `setLastScrollY`, each of which triggers a re-render. Each re-render re-fires the effect, which **adds two more event listeners**. This creates a runaway accumulation loop:

```
Mount          → 2 listeners added
User scrolls   → 3 state updates → 3 re-renders → 6 more listeners (now 8 total)
User scrolls   → 3 state updates → 3 re-renders → 6 more listeners (now 14 total)
...and so on, exponentially
```

---

### Issue 2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Survive Unmount)

When the user navigates away, React unmounts the component — but since the `useEffect` never returns a cleanup function, **every listener registered during the component's lifetime remains attached to `window` forever.**

Navigate away and back 5 times? You now have hundreds of orphaned scroll handlers all firing simultaneously on every scroll event, each calling stale `setState` on an unmounted component.

---

## Why Anonymous Arrow Functions Make Cleanup Impossible

```jsx
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { /* ... */ });
//                                 ↑
//            A brand-new function reference is created every time
```

`removeEventListener` identifies listeners by **reference equality**. An anonymous arrow function creates a new object in memory each time it's evaluated — you can never get the same reference back to pass to `removeEventListener`. Even if you tried to add cleanup, it would silently fail:

```jsx
// This does NOTHING — different reference, never matches
return () => window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
```

You must capture a **named reference** before registering, so the exact same reference can be passed to both `addEventListener` and `removeEventListener`.

---

### Bonus Issue — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up'); // ← stale!
    });
});
```

`lastScrollY` is read from the closure captured at the moment the handler is created. Because scroll direction state is set via `setLastScrollY`, the handler always sees the **value of `lastScrollY` from the render in which it was born** — never the updated value. Scroll direction will be computed incorrectly. A `useRef` is the correct tool here: it's a mutable container that always holds the latest value without triggering re-renders.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Worse in Development

In development, React 18 Strict Mode intentionally **mounts → unmounts → remounts** every component on initial load to help surface missing cleanup. Without the cleanup function, this immediately doubles your listener count before a single user interaction. What takes 5 page navigations to notice in production will manifest as broken behavior on the very first mount in development — this is by design, and it's your early-warning signal that cleanup is missing.

---

## The Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY]               = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // useRef instead of useState for lastScrollY:
    //   1. Doesn't trigger a re-render when updated (prevents the runaway loop)
    //   2. Always holds the latest value (no stale closure on the scroll handler)
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named function references — required so removeEventListener
        // can match the exact same reference that was registered.
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // Read and write via .current — always fresh, never stale
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup function: runs on unmount AND before each re-execution of
        // the effect (though with [] it only runs on unmount).
        // This is what prevents listener accumulation across navigations.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // Empty array: register once on mount, clean up once on unmount.
            // Event listeners don't need re-registration when state changes.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners multiply on every render | No `[]` dependency array | Add `[]` — effect runs once on mount |
| Listeners survive navigation | No cleanup function | Return `() => removeEventListener(...)` |
| Cleanup can't remove listeners | Anonymous arrow functions | Extract named function references |
| Stale scroll direction logic | `lastScrollY` state in closure | Replace with `useRef` |
| Dev bug amplification | React 18 Strict Mode double-invoke | Proper cleanup handles this automatically |

The lifecycle of the corrected component is now clean and predictable:

```
Mount   →  useEffect fires  →  2 listeners registered
↕ user scrolls/resizes  →  handlers fire, state updates, component re-renders
↕ (useEffect does NOT re-fire — dependency array is [])
Unmount →  cleanup function fires  →  both listeners removed, memory freed
```

